## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| **Critical** | 6 |
| **High** | 0 |
| **Medium** | 2 |
| **Low** | 1 |

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test class. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called (achieving high line coverage), but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will pass even if the production code is completely broken — they give false confidence.

---

### 🔴 Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic)

The entire class methodically calls every public method without meaningful assertions. 6 of 10 tests have **zero assertions**; 4 others use only `Assert.IsNotNull` which verifies almost nothing.

#### 2. No Assertions — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)

```csharp
// BEFORE — proves nothing
_catalog.AddProduct(product);

// AFTER — verify the product was actually stored
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var stored = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", stored?.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, stored?.Price);
```

#### 3. No Assertions — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)

```csharp
// BEFORE — price change is never verified
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

// AFTER
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
```

#### 4. No Assertions — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39)

```csharp
// BEFORE — deletion is never verified
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");

// AFTER
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

#### 5. No Assertions — `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)

```csharp
// BEFORE — result discarded entirely
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();

// AFTER
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();
Assert.AreEqual(1, count);
```

#### 6. No Assertions — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 69)

This is the most dangerous gap — a 10% discount calculation could silently produce wrong values.

```csharp
// BEFORE — discount math never verified
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);

// AFTER
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
var widget = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, widget?.Price);   // 9.99 * 0.90
var gadget = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002");
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, gadget?.Price);  // 19.99 * 0.90
```

#### 7. Trivial `IsNotNull` Assertions — `GetProduct`, `SearchProducts`, `GetAllProducts`, `ExportToCsv` (lines 25, 47, 55, 77)

`Assert.IsNotNull` on a collection or string confirms the method returned *something* but never checks correctness. `Search("Widget")` could return `["Gadget"]` and the test would pass.

```csharp
// BEFORE (SearchProducts_Works)
var results = _catalog.Search("Widget");
Assert.IsNotNull(results);

// AFTER — verify actual filtering behavior
var results = _catalog.Search("Widget");
Assert.AreEqual(1, results.Count);
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", results[0].Sku);
```

